               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300527-216-person1776">
                  WILLIAM 
                  WILSON
               <interp inst="t18300527-216-person1776" type="surname" value="WILSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-216-person1776" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-216-person1776" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am in <rs id="t18300527-216-viclabel1144" type="occupation">partner</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300527-216-victim1775 t18300527-216-viclabel1144"></join>ship with two others. The prisoner was in our employ for five years, at our warehouse in <placeName id="t18300527-216-crimeloc1145">Martin's-lane</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18300527-216-crimeloc1145" type="placeName" value="Martin's-lane"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18300527-216-crimeloc1145" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300527-216-off1142 t18300527-216-crimeloc1145"></join>; he was entrusted with the keys to open the gates in the morning. In consequence of information I stopped in the warehouse on Thursday night last, with a witness; I heard the prisoner go into a room and take this property - I saw him before he left the room; the witness was in that room, and I was in the floor above - when I heard him going out of the room I went down, and found him in custody.</p>

               <p>Cross-examined by MR. LEE. Q. Was it not his business to go into that part of the premises? A. No.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300527-216-person1777">
                  JOHN 
                  PING
               <interp inst="t18300527-216-person1777" type="surname" value="PING"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-216-person1777" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-216-person1777" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was in the room, and at half-past five o'clock the prisoner opened the outer gates and came in -I saw him through the window; he came into the room by some means, and searched the pockets of the prosecutor's coat, which hung there - he then spread his handkerchief out, and took out three cakes of soap, and put one of them into his handkerchief; he then went to a cupboard, and took some unfinished hats, but he put them<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183005270100"></xptr>back again - he then took this flour, and was going to leave the room: I seized him in the door-way, and found these articles on him.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Have you ever quarrelled with him? A. No; I told him I thought he did not do his duty by not lighting the fires, and coming in good time - I never said I would do for him; I should be sorry to use such an unmanly expression.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300527-216-person1778">
                  JOHN 
                  FREE
               <interp inst="t18300527-216-person1778" type="surname" value="FREE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-216-person1778" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-216-person1778" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer, and took the prisoner. -These things were given me by the prosecutor, who said he had got them by means of this key; the prisoner said nothing.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. The witness has told a great many lies, to say he never quarrelled with me.</p>
               <p>The prisoner received an excellent character.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 45.</p>
               <p>
